ckage**: `package e2e`\\n   106→- **Parallel**: Always `t.Parallel()` in top-level test functions\\n   107→- **Strategy**: Use `NewFeatureBranchEnv(t, \\\"manual-commit\\\")` for most tests\\n   108→- **Prompts**: Use existing `PromptTemplate` variables from `prompts.go`\\n   109→- **Assertions**: Use existing assertion helpers from `assertions.go`\\n   110→- **No hardcoded paths**: Use `TestEnv` helpers for all file/git operations\\n   111→- **Do NOT run E2E tests**: They make real API calls. Only write the code and print commands.\\n   112→\\n   113→## Output\\n   114→\\n   115→Summarize what was created/modified:\\n   116→- Files added or modified\\n   117→- New agent runner details (how it invokes the agent)\\n   118→- Any agent-specific test scenarios added\\n   119→- Commands to run the tests (for user to execute manually)\\n   120→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"1694ebe2-1c7e-4e04-96e2-cc51ea38940e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T21:42:52.327Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"I need to understand how the agent-integration skill files use hardcoded file paths, and identify which paths are fragile vs stable. \\n\\nRead ALL files in `.claude/skills/agent-integration/` and catalog:\\n\\n1. **Every hardcoded file path** mentioned in the skill files (e.g., `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go`, `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`, etc.)\\n2. For each path, classify it as:\\n   - **Stable**: Core architecture files unlikely to move (e.g., `agent.go`, `event.go`)\\n   - **Fragile**: Specific implementation files, test files, or paths that reference specific directories that could change\\n   - **Nonexistent/Wrong**: Paths that don't actually exist in the repo\\n3. **Pattern**: How are paths used? Are they \\\"required reading\\\" lists? Template code? Reference pointers?\\n4. **Hardcoded details besides paths**: Method counts, function signatures, struct field names, specific runner names — anything that could drift from the actual code\\n\\nAlso check: D