hem entirely, or keep them but with \\\"read the actual interface\\\" caveats?\\n4. What's the right balance between \\\"here's exactly what to read\\\" vs \\\"go discover\\\"?\\n\\nPlease design an approach that makes the skill resilient to codebase evolution without making it so vague that it loses its utility as a guide.\",\"agentId\":\"ae4ef6893ab163f47\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Wvr31ojKCuADWh32JSR2Vb\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01PWEmt8g1qUDtEZEfbD68F3\",\"uuid\":\"ea123fa3-b3fc-4f18-add4-6d8835a349f1\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T21:52:15.944Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"ea123fa3-b3fc-4f18-add4-6d8835a349f1\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"e3b9b251-e322-4a6b-b48d-361a9097e77a\",\"version\":\"2.1.53\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/agent-integration-skill\",\"slug\":\"merry-leaping-turing\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Task\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01PWEmt8g1qUDtEZEfbD68F3\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01PWEmt8g1qUDtEZEfbD68F3\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T21:54:18.208Z\",\"uuid\":\"0d06e9e7-32de-4048-babf-187fba99abf4\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"eff4b906-a8a2-483a-a507-64accb72c201\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"e3b9b251-e322-4a6b-b48d-361a9097e77a\",\"version\":\"2.1.53\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/agent-integration-skill\",\"slug\":\"merry-leaping-turing\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01PWEmt8g1qUDtEZEfbD68F3\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The current Agent interface has 15 methods (6 identity + 3 transcript + 6 legacy), not 19. The guide says 19. Major drift.\\n\\nNow I have a complete picture. Let me design the plan.\\n\\n---\\n\\nHere is the comprehensive design plan for making the agent-integration skill files resilient to codebase evolution.\\n\\n## Analysis Summary\\n\\n### Current Drift Inventory\\n\\nI identified five layers of drift across the four skill prompt files and their upstream sources:\\n\\n**1. The agent-guide.md is itself severely drifted from the actual codebase.** It references removed methods (`HookHandler`, `GetSupportedHooks`, `SupportsHooks`, `GetHookConfigPath`, `ParseHookInput`), uses the renamed `paths.RepoRoot()` instead of `paths.WorktreeRoot()`, and claims \\\"19 methods on the Agent interface\\\" when there are actually 15. The code templates in the guide contain method implementations for interfaces that no longer exist. This is the root cause -- the skill prompts point at an authoritative doc that is itself wrong.\\n\\n**2. The skill prompts duplicate information from the guide.** The probe-prompt says \\\"7 normalized EventTypes: `SessionStart`, `TurnStart`, `TurnEnd`, `Compaction`, `SessionEnd`, `SubagentStart`, `SubagentEnd`\\\" -- this is currently accurate but is a copy of what lives in `event.go`. Any change there means two places to update.\\n\\n**3. Runner/test file enumeration is exhaustive.** The e2e-test-prompt lists all 6 scenario test files by name, all 3 runner types by class name, and all helper files. Any new scenario file or runner added/removed makes the list stale.\\n\\n**4. Code examples embed method signatures.** The implement-prompt shows `InstallHooks(localDev bool, force bool) error` in its template code -- while the actual interface returns `(int, error)`. Code examples go stale faster than prose.\\n\\n**5. Reference implementation descriptions assume stable structure.** Saying `geminicli/` is \\\"File-watcher based hook model\\\" or `opencode/` is \\\"Plugin-based hook model\\\" may not remain accurate as these implementations evolve.\\n\\n### What is Genuinely Stable\\n\\nBased on git log analysis:\\n\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go`** -- changes frequently (20+ commits). NOT stable for literal enumeration, but the *file itself* is the right anchor point since the interface definition always lives here.\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`** -- only 2 commits. Relatively stable, but event types could still be added.\\n- **`docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`** -- only 7 commits, but already heavily drifted. It was written once and not maintained in sync with interface refactors.\\n- **`docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md`** -- 7 commits, more stable in concept but references guide anchors that have drifted.\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`** -- 20+ commits, very volatile. New scenario files and runner modifications happen regularly.\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go`** and **`cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go`** -- 20+ commits, volatile.\\n\\n### Stability Classification for Paths\\n\\n| Path | Stability | Keep Hardcoded? |\\n|------|-----------|----------------|\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` | File exists, content changes | YES -- anchor, tell agent to read it |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` | File exists, content stable-ish | YES -- anchor |\\n| `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` | File exists, content drifted | YES -- anchor, but do NOT copy its contents |\\n| `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` | File exists, content semi-stable | YES -- anchor |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/agent/` (directory) | Exists, subdirs change | YES -- discovery root |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/` (directory) | Exists, files change | YES -- discovery root |\\n| Individual agent dirs (`claudecode/`, etc.) | Volatile | NO -- discover via glob |\\n| Individual test files (`scenario_*_test.go`) | Volatile | NO -- discover via glob |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` | Volatile in content | CONDITIONAL -- keep path, remove content descriptions |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` | Volatile in content | CONDITIONAL -- keep path, remove content descriptions |\\n| Runner class names (`ClaudeCodeRunner`, etc.) | Volatile | NO -- discover from code |\\n\\n## Design Approach: \\\"Anchor + Discover\\\" Pattern\\n\\nThe core principle is: **hardcode stable file paths as entry points, but tell the agent to discover volatile details by reading the actual code.**\\n\\n### Strategy 1: Replace enumerated lists with discovery instructions\\n\\nInstead of listing all event types, interface methods, runner names, or test files, instruct the agent to read the source file and extract the information.\\n\\n**Before (probe-prompt.md line 14):**\\n```\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — 7 normalized EventTypes: `SessionStart`, `TurnStart`, `TurnEnd`, `Compaction`, `SessionEnd`, `SubagentStart`, `SubagentEnd`\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read this file to find all `EventType` constants. These are the normalized lifecycle events your agent must map to.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 2: Replace reference implementation listings with glob patterns\\n\\n**Before (probe-prompt.md lines 22-24):**\\n```\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/` — Most complete, has all optional interfaces\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/` — File-watcher based hook model\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/` — Plugin-based hook model\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\n**Reference implementations:** Run `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Read 1-2 as reference, focusing on `lifecycle.go` (ParseHookEvent), `hooks.go` (HookSupport), and `types.go` (hook input structs) in each.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 3: Replace test file enumeration with glob + pattern description\\n\\n**Before (e2e-test-prompt.md lines 26-31):**\\n```\\n1. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_basic_workflow_test.go` — Basic: ...\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_checkpoint_test.go` — Checkpoint ...\\n...\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_*_test.go\\\")` to find all existing scenario tests. Read each to understand the test patterns and conventions. Also read `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/*_test.go\\\")` for the full test file set.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 4: Remove duplicated code examples, point to source\\n\\nThe implement-prompt contains full TDD code templates for `types.go`, `lifecycle.go`, `hooks.go`, `transcript.go`. These duplicate what is already in `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` (which has its own fuller templates). Rather than maintain code examples in two places, the skill prompts should say \\\"read the reference implementation and the guide for code examples.\\\"\\n\\n**Before (implement-prompt.md Step 7):**\\n```go\\nfunc (a *Agent) InstallHooks(localDev bool, force bool) (int, error) { ... }\\nfunc (a *Agent) UninstallHooks() error { ... }\\nfunc (a *Agent) AreHooksInstalled() bool { ... }\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\nRead the `HookSupport` interface in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` to see the exact method signatures you need to implement. Then read the hooks implementation in a reference agent (find via `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/hooks.go\\\")`) for the pattern.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 5: Replace runner/struct name enumeration with grep discovery\\n\\n**Before (e2e-test-prompt.md line 18):**\\n```\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/agent_runner.go` — `AgentRunner` interface and existing runners (`ClaudeCodeRunner`, `GeminiCLIRunner`, `OpenCodeRunner`)\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/agent_runner.go` — `AgentRunner` interface definition and all existing runner implementations. Read the file to discover all current runners (search for types implementing `AgentRunner`) and the `NewAgentRunner` factory switch statement where you'll add your agent.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 6: Fix agent-guide.md as a prerequisite\\n\\nThe agent-guide.md has severe drift and should be fixed as a prerequisite (or parallel) task. The skill prompts should reference it as authoritative, but only after it is accurate. Changes needed:\\n\\n- Remove references to `HookHandler`, `GetSupportedHooks`, `SupportsHooks`, `GetHookConfigPath`, `ParseHookInput`\\n- Update method count from \\\"19\\\" to match reality (15)\\n- Replace `paths.RepoRoot()` with `paths.WorktreeRoot()` throughout\\n- Remove code templates referencing deleted interfaces\\n- Update the optional interfaces table to match current reality\\n\\nHowever, even after fixing, the guide should itself adopt the same resilience pattern: avoid duplicating what's in the code. The guide's Quick Reference table should say \\\"see `agent.go` for the current interface\\\" rather than attempting to enumerate all methods.\\n\\n## Detailed File-by-File Plan\\n\\n### File 1: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/README.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 6 hardcoded paths, all stable anchors. This file is already fairly resilient.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n- Line 50: Change `Existing agents: cmd/entire/cli/agent/{claudecode,geminicli,opencode}/` to `Existing agents: cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/ (discover via Glob)`. This prevents staleness when agents are added/removed.\\n- All other paths are stable anchors and should stay.\\n\\n### File 2: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/probe-prompt.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 13 paths, enumerated event types, enumerated interface names, enumerated agent descriptions.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n\\n**Required reading section (lines 12-18):** Keep the 6 file paths as anchors. Remove the inline enumerations.\\n\\n| Line | Current | Proposed |\\n|------|---------|----------|\\n| 13 | `agent.go` — The `Agent` interface (core methods + 6 optional capability interfaces) | `agent.go` — Read to find the `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces (e.g., `HookSupport`, `TranscriptAnalyzer`, etc.) |\\n| 14 | `event.go` — 7 normalized EventTypes: `SessionStart`, ... | `event.go` — Read to find all `EventType` constants. These are the lifecycle events the agent must map to. |\\n| 15 | `hook_registry.go` — How native hook names are registered and routed | Keep as-is (description is conceptual, not enumerative) |\\n| 16 | `lifecycle.go` — `DispatchLifecycleEvent` handler | Keep as-is |\\n| 17-18 | Guide + checklist paths | Keep as-is |\\n\\n**Reference implementations section (lines 22-24):** Replace specific agent listings with discovery instruction:\\n```\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to discover all existing agent packages. Pick 1-2 as reference implementations. In each, focus on `lifecycle.go` (ParseHookEvent mapping), `hooks.go` (hook installation), and `types.go` (hook input structs).\\n```\\n\\n**Compatibility report template (lines 109-129):** The EventType table and interface feasibility table in the report template are tricky. These are *output* templates, not input references, so the agent needs to know what to fill in. Two options:\\n\\nOption A: Keep the template but add \\\"populate from source\\\" instructions:\\n```\\n## Lifecycle Event Mapping\\nRead `event.go` for the full EventType list, then fill one row per type:\\n| Entire EventType | Native Hook | Status | Fields Available |\\n...\\n```\\n\\nOption B: Replace with a dynamic instruction:\\n```\\n## Lifecycle Event Mapping\\nFor each EventType constant in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`, create a row mapping it to the agent's native hook (or MISSING).\\n```\\n\\nI recommend Option B. It is more resilient and the agent is capable of generating the table dynamically.\\n\\nSimilarly for the interface feasibility table:\\n```\\n## Required Interface Feasibility\\nFor each interface defined in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` (both the core `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces), assess feasibility.\\n```\\n\\n### File 3: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/e2e-test-prompt.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 16 paths, hardcoded runner names, hardcoded test file names.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n\\n**Step 1 (lines 15-20) -- E2E test infrastructure:** Keep `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/` as the anchor directory. Replace individual file enumeration with a combined anchor + discovery approach.\\n\\n```\\nRead the E2E test infrastructure in `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`:\\n\\n1. `setup_test.go` — TestMain, binary building, agent availability checks\\n2. `testenv.go` — `TestEnv` helpers for isolated test environments\\n3. `agent_runner.go` — `AgentRunner` interface and existing runner implementations (read to discover all current runners)\\n4. `prompts.go` — `PromptTemplate` definitions for deterministic test prompts\\n5. `assertions.go` — Shared assertion helpers\\n```\\n\\nThese 5 filenames (`setup_test.go`, `testenv.go`, `agent_runner.go`, `prompts.go`, `assertions.go`) are structural and stable -- they represent the infrastructure, not individual test cases. Keep them.\\n\\n**Step 2 (lines 25-31) -- Scenario tests:** Replace the exhaustive list with discovery.\\n\\n```\\n### Step 2: Read Existing E2E Scenario Tests\\n\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_*_test.go\\\")` to find all existing scenario tests. Read each to understand the patterns and conventions:\\n- How scenarios use `TestEnv` and `AgentRunner`\\n- How prompts are structured\\n- How assertions validate checkpoints, rewind, etc.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 4 (lines 38-66) -- Create AgentRunner:** The code template with `${AGENT_NAME}Runner` struct is acceptable because it is showing the *new* code to create, not referencing existing code. However, the reference to specific existing runner names should be replaced.\\n\\nReplace line 18's parenthetical:\\n```\\nexisting runners (`ClaudeCodeRunner`, `GeminiCLIRunner`, `OpenCodeRunner`)\\n```\\nwith:\\n```\\nRead the file to discover all existing runner implementations and the `NewAgentRunner` factory.\\n```\\n\\nReplace line 58-59:\\n```\\n- Add `AgentName${AGENT_NAME}` constant (e.g., `const AgentNameWindsurf = \\\"windsurf\\\"`)\\n- Register in `NewAgentRunner` switch statement\\n```\\nwith:\\n```\\n- Add an agent name constant following the pattern of existing constants in `agent_runner.go`\\n- Register in the `NewAgentRunner` switch statement (find it by searching for `func NewAgentRunner`)\\n```\\n\\n### File 4: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/implement-prompt.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 14 paths, code examples with method signatures, TDD cycle with template code.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n\\n**Step 1 (lines 16-20) -- Required reading:** Keep all 4 paths. They are stable anchors. Remove inline descriptions of content (like \\\"Event types and `ReadAndParseHookInput` helper\\\" -- the helper function could be renamed or moved).\\n\\n```\\n1. `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Authoritative implementation guide. Read thoroughly.\\n2. `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Validation criteria for completeness.\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` — Read to find the exact `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces you must implement.\\n4. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read to find `EventType` constants and any shared helpers.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 2 (lines 24-32) -- Reference implementation selection:** Replace the table with discovery.\\n\\n```\\n### Step 2: Read Reference Implementation\\n\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Pick the closest as a template based on the probe findings:\\n\\n- Read a few agents' `hooks.go` files to find one with a similar hook mechanism to your target agent\\n- For JSON config hook mechanisms, look for agents that modify a settings file\\n- For file-based detection, look for agents implementing `FileWatcher`\\n- For plugin/extension systems, look for the most similar pattern\\n\\nRead all `*.go` files (skip `*_test.go` on first pass) in the chosen reference.\\n```\\n\\n**Steps 4-9 -- TDD cycles:** The code templates here are prescriptive (showing what to write) rather than descriptive (describing what exists). This is fine for stable patterns, but the method signatures embedded in these templates WILL drift. The solution:\\n\\nFor each TDD step, replace inline code examples with \\\"read the interface, follow the pattern\\\":\\n\\nStep 5 example:\\n```\\n**Green**: Create `${AGENT_SLUG}.go`. Read the `Agent` interface in `agent.go` to see all methods you need to implement. Follow the structure of a reference agent (e.g., the main `.go` file in one of the agent packages found via Glob).\\n```\\n\\nStep 6 example:\\n```\\n**Green**: Create `lifecycle.go`. Read the `HookSupport` interface in `agent.go` for the exact `ParseHookEvent` signature. Read a reference agent's `lifecycle.go` for the switch-case pattern mapping native hooks to `EventType` constants.\\n```\\n\\nStep 7 example:\\n```\\n**Green**: Create `hooks.go`. Read the `HookSupport` interface in `agent.go` for the exact `InstallHooks`, `UninstallHooks`, and `AreHooksInstalled` signatures. Read a reference agent's `hooks.go` for the implementation pattern.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 9 (lines 213-221) -- Optional interfaces:** Replace the bullet list of interface names with a discovery instruction.\\n\\n```\\nRead `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` to find all optional interfaces beyond `Agent` and `HookSupport`. For each optional interface that the probe report marked as feasible, follow the same TDD cycle.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 10 (lines 223-227) -- Register and Wire Up:** The instruction \\\"Search `cmd/entire/cli/` for where hook subcommands are registered\\\" is already a discovery pattern -- keep it.\\n\\n### Prerequisite: Fix `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`\\n\\nThis should happen first or in parallel, since the skill prompts delegate authority to it. Required fixes:\\n\\n1. Remove all references to deleted interfaces/methods: `HookHandler`, `GetSupportedHooks`, `SupportsHooks`, `GetHookConfigPath`, `ParseHookInput`\\n2. Update \\\"19 methods\\\" to actual count (15) -- or better, remove the count entirely and say \\\"Read `agent.go` for the current interface definition\\\"\\n3. Replace all `paths.RepoRoot()` with `paths.WorktreeRoot()`\\n4. Update code templates to only include methods that exist on current interfaces\\n5. Remove `HookHandler` interface assertion example\\n6. Update the Optional Interfaces table to remove `HookHandler` and `GetSupportedHooks`\\n\\n### Consideration: Should agent-guide.md also adopt the \\\"anchor + discover\\\" pattern?\\n\\nThe guide serves a different audience -- it may be read by humans in a browser, not just by AI agents with tool access. For the guide, the right balance is:\\n\\n- Keep the conceptual tables (event mapping, optional interface decision tree) since humans reading the guide need them\\n- Add a caveat at the top: \\\"Method signatures shown here are illustrative. Always verify against the actual interface in `agent.go`.\\\"\\n- Remove specific method counts that go stale\\n\\n## Implementation Sequence\\n\\n1. **Fix `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`** -- Remove stale references, update function names, remove hardcoded counts. This is the foundation.\\n\\n2. **Rewrite `probe-prompt.md`** -- Apply the anchor + discover pattern. This is the most heavily enumerated file.\\n\\n3. **Rewrite `e2e-test-prompt.md`** -- Replace test file and runner enumeration with Glob-based discovery.\\n\\n4. **Rewrite `implement-prompt.md`** -- Replace code templates with \\\"read the interface + reference\\\" instructions.\\n\\n5. **Update `README.md`** -- Minor change to the existing agents line.\\n\\n6. **Update `SKILL.md`** -- Check if any of the changes affect the skill definition. Currently it does not contain volatile references, so no changes needed.\\n\\n## Answering the Design Questions\\n\\n**1. Which paths should stay hardcoded (stable anchors)?**\\n\\nThese 8 paths should remain hardcoded across all skill files:\\n\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` -- Interface definitions live here, always will\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` -- EventType constants, rarely changes\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` -- Hook routing logic\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` -- Event dispatching\\n- `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` -- Authoritative guide\\n- `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` -- Validation criteria\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/agent_runner.go` -- AgentRunner interface + factory\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/testenv.go` -- TestEnv helpers\\n\\nAnd these 5 infrastructure test files (names are structural):\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/setup_test.go`\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/prompts.go`\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/assertions.go`\\n- `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md`\\n\\n**2. Which should be replaced with discovery patterns?**\\n\\n- All individual agent package listings (`claudecode/`, `geminicli/`, `opencode/`) -- use `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` \\n- All scenario test file listings (`scenario_*_test.go`) -- use `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_*_test.go\\\")`\\n- EventType name enumeration -- say \\\"read event.go\\\"\\n- Optional interface name enumeration -- say \\\"read agent.go\\\"\\n- Runner class names -- say \\\"read agent_runner.go\\\"\\n- Agent name constants -- say \\\"find existing constants in agent_runner.go\\\"\\n\\n**3. How should code examples be handled?**\\n\\nRemove inline code examples from skill prompts entirely. Replace with:\\n- \\\"Read the interface in `agent.go` for the exact signatures\\\"\\n- \\\"Read a reference agent's `lifecycle.go` for the switch-case pattern\\\"\\n- \\\"The `agent-guide.md` contains full code templates\\\" (after that guide is fixed)\\n\\nThe agent-guide.md should keep its code templates but add a caveat that signatures should be verified against `agent.go`. The skill prompts should NOT duplicate those templates.\\n\\n**4. What is the right balance between \\\"here is exactly what to read\\\" vs \\\"go discover\\\"?**\\n\\nThe rule of thumb: **hardcode the WHERE, discover the WHAT.**\\n\\n- Hardcode file paths that tell the agent where to look (the \\\"anchor points\\\")\\n- Use discovery (Glob, Grep, \\\"read the file\\\") for specific names, counts, method signatures, and enumerations that live inside those files\\n- Keep structural knowledge (e.g., \\\"there is a factory switch in `NewAgentRunner`\\\") but not specific names (e.g., \\\"it currently has `ClaudeCodeRunner`, `GeminiCLIRunner`, `OpenCodeRunner`\\\")\\n\\n### Critical Files for Implementation\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` - Must be fixed first; has severe drift from actual interfaces (deleted methods, wrong function names, stale method counts)\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/agent-integration/probe-prompt.md` - Most heavily enumerated file; needs event types, interface names, and agent listings replaced with discovery patterns\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/agent-integration/e2e-test-prompt.md` - Test file and runner enumeration needs Glob-based discovery\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/agent-integration/implement-prompt.md` - Code templates with method signatures need replacement with \\\"read the interface\\\" instructions\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` - The source of truth; skill prompts should always defer to this file for interface definitions\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: ae4ef6893ab163f47 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 90102\\ntool_uses: 36\\nduration_ms: 270633</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"ed2d2e20-6537-4baa-8dc4-143ab67f3234\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T21:54:18.207Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"I need to redesign agent-integration skill files to be less dependent on exact file paths, reducing maintenance burden when the codebase evolves.\\n\\n## Current state\\nThe skill has 4 prompt files under `.claude/skills/agent-integration/`:\\n- `README.md` — overview with 6 paths\\n- `probe-prompt.md` — probe phase, 13 paths + hardcoded event type names\\n- `e2e-test-prompt.md` — E2E test generation, 16 paths + hardcoded runner/test file names  \\n- `implement-prompt.md` — TDD implementation, 14 paths + hardcoded method signatures\\n\\n## Types of hardcoded references that cause drift\\n\\n1. **\\\"Required reading\\\" lists** — Numbered lists of exact file paths that must be read before starting. Example from probe-prompt.md:\\n```\\n1. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` — The `Agent` interface\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — 7 normalized EventTypes\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` — How native hook names are registered\\n4. `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` — `DispatchLifecycleEvent` handler\\n5. `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Full implementation guide\\n6. `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Validation criteria\\n```\\n\\n2. **Enumeration of specific names** — Lists like `(ClaudeCodeRunner, GeminiCLIRunner, OpenCodeRunner)` or event types `SessionStart, TurnStart, TurnEnd, Compaction, SessionEnd, SubagentStart, SubagentEnd` that go stale when items are added/removed/renamed.\\n\\n3. **Code examples with method signatures** — Template code showing exact function signatures like `InstallHooks(localDev bool, force bool) error` that was already wrong (should be `(int, error)`).\\n\\n4. **Specific test file names** — `scenario_basic_workflow_test.go`, `scenario_checkpoint_test.go`, etc.\\n\\n5. **Reference implementation directory listings** — `claudecode/`, `geminicli/`, `opencode/` with descriptions of their hook models.\\n\\n## What we already have that helps\\n- `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — comprehensive implementation guide\\n- `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — validation criteria\\n- The agent running these skills has access to Read, Glob, Grep tools\\n\\n## Design constraints\\n- These are prompts for an AI agent (Claude Code) that has full codebase access\\n- The agent can read files, grep, glob — so we can tell it to discover things rather than listing them\\n- The prompts should still provide enough structure to guide the implementation correctly\\n- We should NOT remove ALL paths — stable anchor points like `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` are useful\\n- The key docs (`agent-guide.md`, `agent-integration-checklist.md`) are the authoritative sources and should be referenced\\n\\n## Questions to answer in the plan\\n1. Which paths should stay hardcoded (stable anchors)?\\n2. Which should be replaced with discovery patterns (glob/grep instructions)?\\n3. How should code examples be handled — remove them entirely, or keep them but with \\\"read the actual interface\\\" caveats?\\n4. What's the right balance between \\\"here's exactly what to read\\\" vs \\\"go discover\\\"?\\n\\nPlease design an approach that makes the skill resilient to codebase evolution without making it so vague that it loses its utility as a guide.\",\"agentId\":\"ae4ef6893ab163f47\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The current Agent interface has 15 methods (6 identity + 3 transcript + 6 legacy), not 19. The guide says 19. Major drift.\\n\\nNow I have a complete picture. Let me design the plan.\\n\\n---\\n\\nHere is the comprehensive design plan for making the agent-integration skill files resilient to codebase evolution.\\n\\n## Analysis Summary\\n\\n### Current Drift Inventory\\n\\nI identified five layers of drift across the four skill prompt files and their upstream sources:\\n\\n**1. The agent-guide.md is itself severely drifted from the actual codebase.** It references removed methods (`HookHandler`, `GetSupportedHooks`, `SupportsHooks`, `GetHookConfigPath`, `ParseHookInput`), uses the renamed `paths.RepoRoot()` instead of `paths.WorktreeRoot()`, and claims \\\"19 methods on the Agent interface\\\" when there are actually 15. The code templates in the guide contain method implementations for interfaces that no longer exist. This is the root cause -- the skill prompts point at an authoritative doc that is itself wrong.\\n\\n**2. The skill prompts duplicate information from the guide.** The probe-prompt says \\\"7 normalized EventTypes: `SessionStart`, `TurnStart`, `TurnEnd`, `Compaction`, `SessionEnd`, `SubagentStart`, `SubagentEnd`\\\" -- this is currently accurate but is a copy of what lives in `event.go`. Any change there means two places to update.\\n\\n**3. Runner/test file enumeration is exhaustive.** The e2e-test-prompt lists all 6 scenario test files by name, all 3 runner types by class name, and all helper files. Any new scenario file or runner added/removed makes the list stale.\\n\\n**4. Code examples embed method signatures.** The implement-prompt shows `InstallHooks(localDev bool, force bool) error` in its template code -- while the actual interface returns `(int, error)`. Code examples go stale faster than prose.\\n\\n**5. Reference implementation descriptions assume stable structure.** Saying `geminicli/` is \\\"File-watcher based hook model\\\" or `opencode/` is \\\"Plugin-based hook model\\\" may not remain accurate as these implementations evolve.\\n\\n### What is Genuinely Stable\\n\\nBased on git log analysis:\\n\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go`** -- changes frequently (20+ commits). NOT stable for literal enumeration, but the *file itself* is the right anchor point since the interface definition always lives here.\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`** -- only 2 commits. Relatively stable, but event types could still be added.\\n- **`docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`** -- only 7 commits, but already heavily drifted. It was written once and not maintained in sync with interface refactors.\\n- **`docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md`** -- 7 commits, more stable in concept but references guide anchors that have drifted.\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`** -- 20+ commits, very volatile. New scenario files and runner modifications happen regularly.\\n- **`cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go`** and **`cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go`** -- 20+ commits, volatile.\\n\\n### Stability Classification for Paths\\n\\n| Path | Stability | Keep Hardcoded? |\\n|------|-----------|----------------|\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` | File exists, content changes | YES -- anchor, tell agent to read it |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` | File exists, content stable-ish | YES -- anchor |\\n| `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` | File exists, content drifted | YES -- anchor, but do NOT copy its contents |\\n| `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` | File exists, content semi-stable | YES -- anchor |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/agent/` (directory) | Exists, subdirs change | YES -- discovery root |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/` (directory) | Exists, files change | YES -- discovery root |\\n| Individual agent dirs (`claudecode/`, etc.) | Volatile | NO -- discover via glob |\\n| Individual test files (`scenario_*_test.go`) | Volatile | NO -- discover via glob |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` | Volatile in content | CONDITIONAL -- keep path, remove content descriptions |\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` | Volatile in content | CONDITIONAL -- keep path, remove content descriptions |\\n| Runner class names (`ClaudeCodeRunner`, etc.) | Volatile | NO -- discover from code |\\n\\n## Design Approach: \\\"Anchor + Discover\\\" Pattern\\n\\nThe core principle is: **hardcode stable file paths as entry points, but tell the agent to discover volatile details by reading the actual code.**\\n\\n### Strategy 1: Replace enumerated lists with discovery instructions\\n\\nInstead of listing all event types, interface methods, runner names, or test files, instruct the agent to read the source file and extract the information.\\n\\n**Before (probe-prompt.md line 14):**\\n```\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — 7 normalized EventTypes: `SessionStart`, `TurnStart`, `TurnEnd`, `Compaction`, `SessionEnd`, `SubagentStart`, `SubagentEnd`\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read this file to find all `EventType` constants. These are the normalized lifecycle events your agent must map to.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 2: Replace reference implementation listings with glob patterns\\n\\n**Before (probe-prompt.md lines 22-24):**\\n```\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/` — Most complete, has all optional interfaces\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/geminicli/` — File-watcher based hook model\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/` — Plugin-based hook model\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\n**Reference implementations:** Run `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Read 1-2 as reference, focusing on `lifecycle.go` (ParseHookEvent), `hooks.go` (HookSupport), and `types.go` (hook input structs) in each.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 3: Replace test file enumeration with glob + pattern description\\n\\n**Before (e2e-test-prompt.md lines 26-31):**\\n```\\n1. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_basic_workflow_test.go` — Basic: ...\\n2. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_checkpoint_test.go` — Checkpoint ...\\n...\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_*_test.go\\\")` to find all existing scenario tests. Read each to understand the test patterns and conventions. Also read `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/*_test.go\\\")` for the full test file set.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 4: Remove duplicated code examples, point to source\\n\\nThe implement-prompt contains full TDD code templates for `types.go`, `lifecycle.go`, `hooks.go`, `transcript.go`. These duplicate what is already in `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` (which has its own fuller templates). Rather than maintain code examples in two places, the skill prompts should say \\\"read the reference implementation and the guide for code examples.\\\"\\n\\n**Before (implement-prompt.md Step 7):**\\n```go\\nfunc (a *Agent) InstallHooks(localDev bool, force bool) (int, error) { ... }\\nfunc (a *Agent) UninstallHooks() error { ... }\\nfunc (a *Agent) AreHooksInstalled() bool { ... }\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\nRead the `HookSupport` interface in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` to see the exact method signatures you need to implement. Then read the hooks implementation in a reference agent (find via `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/hooks.go\\\")`) for the pattern.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 5: Replace runner/struct name enumeration with grep discovery\\n\\n**Before (e2e-test-prompt.md line 18):**\\n```\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/agent_runner.go` — `AgentRunner` interface and existing runners (`ClaudeCodeRunner`, `GeminiCLIRunner`, `OpenCodeRunner`)\\n```\\n\\n**After:**\\n```\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/agent_runner.go` — `AgentRunner` interface definition and all existing runner implementations. Read the file to discover all current runners (search for types implementing `AgentRunner`) and the `NewAgentRunner` factory switch statement where you'll add your agent.\\n```\\n\\n### Strategy 6: Fix agent-guide.md as a prerequisite\\n\\nThe agent-guide.md has severe drift and should be fixed as a prerequisite (or parallel) task. The skill prompts should reference it as authoritative, but only after it is accurate. Changes needed:\\n\\n- Remove references to `HookHandler`, `GetSupportedHooks`, `SupportsHooks`, `GetHookConfigPath`, `ParseHookInput`\\n- Update method count from \\\"19\\\" to match reality (15)\\n- Replace `paths.RepoRoot()` with `paths.WorktreeRoot()` throughout\\n- Remove code templates referencing deleted interfaces\\n- Update the optional interfaces table to match current reality\\n\\nHowever, even after fixing, the guide should itself adopt the same resilience pattern: avoid duplicating what's in the code. The guide's Quick Reference table should say \\\"see `agent.go` for the current interface\\\" rather than attempting to enumerate all methods.\\n\\n## Detailed File-by-File Plan\\n\\n### File 1: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/README.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 6 hardcoded paths, all stable anchors. This file is already fairly resilient.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n- Line 50: Change `Existing agents: cmd/entire/cli/agent/{claudecode,geminicli,opencode}/` to `Existing agents: cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/ (discover via Glob)`. This prevents staleness when agents are added/removed.\\n- All other paths are stable anchors and should stay.\\n\\n### File 2: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/probe-prompt.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 13 paths, enumerated event types, enumerated interface names, enumerated agent descriptions.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n\\n**Required reading section (lines 12-18):** Keep the 6 file paths as anchors. Remove the inline enumerations.\\n\\n| Line | Current | Proposed |\\n|------|---------|----------|\\n| 13 | `agent.go` — The `Agent` interface (core methods + 6 optional capability interfaces) | `agent.go` — Read to find the `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces (e.g., `HookSupport`, `TranscriptAnalyzer`, etc.) |\\n| 14 | `event.go` — 7 normalized EventTypes: `SessionStart`, ... | `event.go` — Read to find all `EventType` constants. These are the lifecycle events the agent must map to. |\\n| 15 | `hook_registry.go` — How native hook names are registered and routed | Keep as-is (description is conceptual, not enumerative) |\\n| 16 | `lifecycle.go` — `DispatchLifecycleEvent` handler | Keep as-is |\\n| 17-18 | Guide + checklist paths | Keep as-is |\\n\\n**Reference implementations section (lines 22-24):** Replace specific agent listings with discovery instruction:\\n```\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to discover all existing agent packages. Pick 1-2 as reference implementations. In each, focus on `lifecycle.go` (ParseHookEvent mapping), `hooks.go` (hook installation), and `types.go` (hook input structs).\\n```\\n\\n**Compatibility report template (lines 109-129):** The EventType table and interface feasibility table in the report template are tricky. These are *output* templates, not input references, so the agent needs to know what to fill in. Two options:\\n\\nOption A: Keep the template but add \\\"populate from source\\\" instructions:\\n```\\n## Lifecycle Event Mapping\\nRead `event.go` for the full EventType list, then fill one row per type:\\n| Entire EventType | Native Hook | Status | Fields Available |\\n...\\n```\\n\\nOption B: Replace with a dynamic instruction:\\n```\\n## Lifecycle Event Mapping\\nFor each EventType constant in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go`, create a row mapping it to the agent's native hook (or MISSING).\\n```\\n\\nI recommend Option B. It is more resilient and the agent is capable of generating the table dynamically.\\n\\nSimilarly for the interface feasibility table:\\n```\\n## Required Interface Feasibility\\nFor each interface defined in `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` (both the core `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces), assess feasibility.\\n```\\n\\n### File 3: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/e2e-test-prompt.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 16 paths, hardcoded runner names, hardcoded test file names.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n\\n**Step 1 (lines 15-20) -- E2E test infrastructure:** Keep `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/` as the anchor directory. Replace individual file enumeration with a combined anchor + discovery approach.\\n\\n```\\nRead the E2E test infrastructure in `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`:\\n\\n1. `setup_test.go` — TestMain, binary building, agent availability checks\\n2. `testenv.go` — `TestEnv` helpers for isolated test environments\\n3. `agent_runner.go` — `AgentRunner` interface and existing runner implementations (read to discover all current runners)\\n4. `prompts.go` — `PromptTemplate` definitions for deterministic test prompts\\n5. `assertions.go` — Shared assertion helpers\\n```\\n\\nThese 5 filenames (`setup_test.go`, `testenv.go`, `agent_runner.go`, `prompts.go`, `assertions.go`) are structural and stable -- they represent the infrastructure, not individual test cases. Keep them.\\n\\n**Step 2 (lines 25-31) -- Scenario tests:** Replace the exhaustive list with discovery.\\n\\n```\\n### Step 2: Read Existing E2E Scenario Tests\\n\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_*_test.go\\\")` to find all existing scenario tests. Read each to understand the patterns and conventions:\\n- How scenarios use `TestEnv` and `AgentRunner`\\n- How prompts are structured\\n- How assertions validate checkpoints, rewind, etc.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 4 (lines 38-66) -- Create AgentRunner:** The code template with `${AGENT_NAME}Runner` struct is acceptable because it is showing the *new* code to create, not referencing existing code. However, the reference to specific existing runner names should be replaced.\\n\\nReplace line 18's parenthetical:\\n```\\nexisting runners (`ClaudeCodeRunner`, `GeminiCLIRunner`, `OpenCodeRunner`)\\n```\\nwith:\\n```\\nRead the file to discover all existing runner implementations and the `NewAgentRunner` factory.\\n```\\n\\nReplace line 58-59:\\n```\\n- Add `AgentName${AGENT_NAME}` constant (e.g., `const AgentNameWindsurf = \\\"windsurf\\\"`)\\n- Register in `NewAgentRunner` switch statement\\n```\\nwith:\\n```\\n- Add an agent name constant following the pattern of existing constants in `agent_runner.go`\\n- Register in the `NewAgentRunner` switch statement (find it by searching for `func NewAgentRunner`)\\n```\\n\\n### File 4: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/implement-prompt.md`\\n\\n**Current state:** 14 paths, code examples with method signatures, TDD cycle with template code.\\n\\n**Changes needed:**\\n\\n**Step 1 (lines 16-20) -- Required reading:** Keep all 4 paths. They are stable anchors. Remove inline descriptions of content (like \\\"Event types and `ReadAndParseHookInput` helper\\\" -- the helper function could be renamed or moved).\\n\\n```\\n1. `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Authoritative implementation guide. Read thoroughly.\\n2. `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Validation criteria for completeness.\\n3. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` — Read to find the exact `Agent` interface and all optional interfaces you must implement.\\n4. `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` — Read to find `EventType` constants and any shared helpers.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 2 (lines 24-32) -- Reference implementation selection:** Replace the table with discovery.\\n\\n```\\n### Step 2: Read Reference Implementation\\n\\nRun `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` to find all existing agent packages. Pick the closest as a template based on the probe findings:\\n\\n- Read a few agents' `hooks.go` files to find one with a similar hook mechanism to your target agent\\n- For JSON config hook mechanisms, look for agents that modify a settings file\\n- For file-based detection, look for agents implementing `FileWatcher`\\n- For plugin/extension systems, look for the most similar pattern\\n\\nRead all `*.go` files (skip `*_test.go` on first pass) in the chosen reference.\\n```\\n\\n**Steps 4-9 -- TDD cycles:** The code templates here are prescriptive (showing what to write) rather than descriptive (describing what exists). This is fine for stable patterns, but the method signatures embedded in these templates WILL drift. The solution:\\n\\nFor each TDD step, replace inline code examples with \\\"read the interface, follow the pattern\\\":\\n\\nStep 5 example:\\n```\\n**Green**: Create `${AGENT_SLUG}.go`. Read the `Agent` interface in `agent.go` to see all methods you need to implement. Follow the structure of a reference agent (e.g., the main `.go` file in one of the agent packages found via Glob).\\n```\\n\\nStep 6 example:\\n```\\n**Green**: Create `lifecycle.go`. Read the `HookSupport` interface in `agent.go` for the exact `ParseHookEvent` signature. Read a reference agent's `lifecycle.go` for the switch-case pattern mapping native hooks to `EventType` constants.\\n```\\n\\nStep 7 example:\\n```\\n**Green**: Create `hooks.go`. Read the `HookSupport` interface in `agent.go` for the exact `InstallHooks`, `UninstallHooks`, and `AreHooksInstalled` signatures. Read a reference agent's `hooks.go` for the implementation pattern.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 9 (lines 213-221) -- Optional interfaces:** Replace the bullet list of interface names with a discovery instruction.\\n\\n```\\nRead `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` to find all optional interfaces beyond `Agent` and `HookSupport`. For each optional interface that the probe report marked as feasible, follow the same TDD cycle.\\n```\\n\\n**Step 10 (lines 223-227) -- Register and Wire Up:** The instruction \\\"Search `cmd/entire/cli/` for where hook subcommands are registered\\\" is already a discovery pattern -- keep it.\\n\\n### Prerequisite: Fix `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`\\n\\nThis should happen first or in parallel, since the skill prompts delegate authority to it. Required fixes:\\n\\n1. Remove all references to deleted interfaces/methods: `HookHandler`, `GetSupportedHooks`, `SupportsHooks`, `GetHookConfigPath`, `ParseHookInput`\\n2. Update \\\"19 methods\\\" to actual count (15) -- or better, remove the count entirely and say \\\"Read `agent.go` for the current interface definition\\\"\\n3. Replace all `paths.RepoRoot()` with `paths.WorktreeRoot()`\\n4. Update code templates to only include methods that exist on current interfaces\\n5. Remove `HookHandler` interface assertion example\\n6. Update the Optional Interfaces table to remove `HookHandler` and `GetSupportedHooks`\\n\\n### Consideration: Should agent-guide.md also adopt the \\\"anchor + discover\\\" pattern?\\n\\nThe guide serves a different audience -- it may be read by humans in a browser, not just by AI agents with tool access. For the guide, the right balance is:\\n\\n- Keep the conceptual tables (event mapping, optional interface decision tree) since humans reading the guide need them\\n- Add a caveat at the top: \\\"Method signatures shown here are illustrative. Always verify against the actual interface in `agent.go`.\\\"\\n- Remove specific method counts that go stale\\n\\n## Implementation Sequence\\n\\n1. **Fix `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md`** -- Remove stale references, update function names, remove hardcoded counts. This is the foundation.\\n\\n2. **Rewrite `probe-prompt.md`** -- Apply the anchor + discover pattern. This is the most heavily enumerated file.\\n\\n3. **Rewrite `e2e-test-prompt.md`** -- Replace test file and runner enumeration with Glob-based discovery.\\n\\n4. **Rewrite `implement-prompt.md`** -- Replace code templates with \\\"read the interface + reference\\\" instructions.\\n\\n5. **Update `README.md`** -- Minor change to the existing agents line.\\n\\n6. **Update `SKILL.md`** -- Check if any of the changes affect the skill definition. Currently it does not contain volatile references, so no changes needed.\\n\\n## Answering the Design Questions\\n\\n**1. Which paths should stay hardcoded (stable anchors)?**\\n\\nThese 8 paths should remain hardcoded across all skill files:\\n\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` -- Interface definitions live here, always will\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/event.go` -- EventType constants, rarely changes\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go` -- Hook routing logic\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go` -- Event dispatching\\n- `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` -- Authoritative guide\\n- `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` -- Validation criteria\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/agent_runner.go` -- AgentRunner interface + factory\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/testenv.go` -- TestEnv helpers\\n\\nAnd these 5 infrastructure test files (names are structural):\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/setup_test.go`\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/prompts.go`\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/assertions.go`\\n- `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md`\\n\\n**2. Which should be replaced with discovery patterns?**\\n\\n- All individual agent package listings (`claudecode/`, `geminicli/`, `opencode/`) -- use `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/agent/*/\\\")` \\n- All scenario test file listings (`scenario_*_test.go`) -- use `Glob(\\\"cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/scenario_*_test.go\\\")`\\n- EventType name enumeration -- say \\\"read event.go\\\"\\n- Optional interface name enumeration -- say \\\"read agent.go\\\"\\n- Runner class names -- say \\\"read agent_runner.go\\\"\\n- Agent name constants -- say \\\"find existing constants in agent_runner.go\\\"\\n\\n**3. How should code examples be handled?**\\n\\nRemove inline code examples from skill prompts entirely. Replace with:\\n- \\\"Read the interface in `agent.go` for the exact signatures\\\"\\n- \\\"Read a reference agent's `lifecycle.go` for the switch-case pattern\\\"\\n- \\\"The `agent-guide.md` contains full code templates\\\" (after that guide is fixed)\\n\\nThe agent-guide.md should keep its code templates but add a caveat that signatures should be verified against `agent.go`. The skill prompts should NOT duplicate those templates.\\n\\n**4. What is the right balance between \\\"here is exactly what to read\\\" vs \\\"go discover\\\"?**\\n\\nThe rule of thumb: **hardcode the WHERE, discover the WHAT.**\\n\\n- Hardcode file paths that tell the agent where to look (the \\\"anchor points\\\")\\n- Use discovery (Glob, Grep, \\\"read the file\\\") for specific names, counts, method signatures, and enumerations that live inside those files\\n- Keep structural knowledge (e.g., \\\"there is a factory switch in `NewAgentRunner`\\\") but not specific names (e.g., \\\"it currently has `ClaudeCodeRunner`, `GeminiCLIRunner`, `OpenCodeRunner`\\\")\\n\\n### Critical Files for Implementation\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` - Must be fixed first; has severe drift from actual interfaces (deleted methods, wrong function names, stale method counts)\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/agent-integration/probe-prompt.md` - Most heavily enumerated file; needs event types, interface names, and agent listings replaced with discovery patterns\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/devenv/cli/.claude/skills/agent-integration/e2e-test-prompt.md` - Test file and runner enumeration needs Glob-based discovery\\n- `/Users/alisha/Projects/dev